Based on the provided documentation, here are the step-by-step instructions to deploy a containerized application on AWS ECS:

**Step 1: Choose a Launch Type**

You can choose between Fargate launch type (serverless pay-as-you-go option) or EC2 launch type (configure and deploy EC2 instances in your cluster). [Source: aws/ECS/Application architecture<a name="application_architecture"></a>]

**AWS > ECS > Application architecture**

* If you choose Fargate, proceed to Step 3.
* If you choose EC2, configure and deploy EC2 instances in your cluster.

**Step 2: Register an External Instance (if using EC2)**

If you chose the EC2 launch type, register an external instance to your cluster. [Source: aws/ECS/Running workloads on external instances<a name="ecs-anywhere-runtask"></a>]

* After registering an external instance, create a task definition and use the `requiresCompatibilities` parameter to validate the task definition is compatible with your external instances.
* When deploying your workload, use the `EXTERNAL` launch type when creating your service or running your standalone task.

**Step 3: Define a Containerized Application using AWS CDK**

Use the AWS CDK to define a containerized application on Fargate. [Source: aws/ECS/Getting started with Amazon ECS using the AWS CDK<a name="tutorial-ecs-web-server-cdk"></a>]

* Use the container image from DockerHub (e.g., `amazon/amazon-ecs-sample`) that contains a PHP web app running on Amazon Linux 2.
* Edit the file containing the stack definition to resemble one of the following examples:
```
import * as ec2 from '@aws-cdk/aws-ec2';
import * as ecs from '@aws-cdk/aws-ecs';

export class MyStack extends cdk.Stack {
  constructor(scope: cdk.Construct, id: string, props?: cdk.StackProps) {
    super(scope, id, props);

    const vpc = new ec2.Vpc(this, 'VPC');

    const cluster = new ecs.Cluster(this, 'Cluster', {
      vpc,
    });

    const taskDefinition = new ecs.TaskDefinition(this, 'TaskDefinition', {
      family: 'my-task-definition',
      requiresCompatibilities: ['FARGATE'],
    });

    const container = new ecs.ContainerDefinition(this, 'Container', {
      image: ecs.ContainerImage.fromRegistry('amazon/amazon-ecs-sample'),
      taskDefinition,
    });
  }
}
```
**Step 4: Deploy the Application**

Deploy the application using AWS CDK. [Source: aws/ECS/Getting started with Amazon ECS using the AWS CDK<a name="tutorial-ecs-web-server-cdk"></a>]

* Use the `app.synth()` method to deploy the stack.

Note that these instructions are based on the provided documentation and may not cover all possible scenarios or edge cases.

Based on the provided documentation, here are the steps to secure an AWS VPC using IAM policies:

**Step 1: Create an IAM policy with read-only access**

Create a new IAM policy with read-only access to your VPC. This policy will allow users to view resources in your VPC without making any changes.

[Source: aws/EC2/Example policies for working with the AWS CLI or an AWS SDK<a name="ExamplePolicies_EC2"></a> > Read\-only access](#iam-example-read-only)

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "ReadOnlyAccess",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "ec2:Describe*"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
```

**Step 2: Attach the IAM policy to an IAM role**

Attach the IAM policy created in Step 1 to an IAM role. This will allow users with this role to access your VPC with read-only permissions.

[Source: aws/EC2/Example policies for working with the AWS CLI or an AWS SDK<a name="ExamplePolicies_EC2"></a> > Example: Allow a specific instance to view resources in other AWS services](#iam-example-source-instance)

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "ReadOnlyAccess",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "ec2:Describe*"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    },
    {
      "Sid": "SourceInstanceARN",
      "Effect": "Condition",
      "Action": "ec2:*",
      "Resource": "*",
      "Condition": {
        "StringLikeIfExists": {
          "ec2:SourceInstanceArn": "arn:aws:ec2:region:account-id:instance/i-093452212644b0dd6"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

**Step 3: Create an IAM policy with full permissions to work with ClassicLink**

Create a new IAM policy with full permissions to work with ClassicLink. This policy will allow users to enable and disable VPCs for ClassicLink, link instances, and unlink instances.

[Source: aws/EC2/ClassicLink<a name="vpc-classiclink"></a> > Example IAM policies for ClassicLink<a name="iam-example-classiclink"></a> > Full permissions to work with ClassicLink](#iam-example-classiclink-full)

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "FullPermissions",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "ec2:Describe*",
        "ec2:CreateVpcClassicLink",
        "ec2:DeleteVpcClassicLink",
        "ec2:CreateVpcClassicLinkDnsSupport",
        "ec2:ModifyVpcClassicLinkDnsSupport"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
```

**Step 4: Attach the IAM policy to an IAM role**

Attach the IAM policy created in Step 3 to an IAM role. This will allow users with this role to access your VPC with full permissions to work with ClassicLink.

[Source: aws/EC2/ClassicLink<a name="vpc-classiclink"></a> > Example IAM policies for ClassicLink<a name="iam-example-classiclink"></a> > Full permissions to work with ClassicLink](#iam-example-classiclink-full)

By following these steps, you can secure your AWS VPC using IAM policies.

Note: These are just examples of IAM policies and may need to be modified based on your specific use case. It's also important to note that IAM policies should be reviewed and updated regularly to ensure they remain effective and up-to-date.

Based on the provided context, here are the step-by-step instructions to monitor AWS Lambda with CloudWatch:

**Step 1: Create an IAM Role for your Lambda Function**
Create an IAM role that allows your Lambda function to write logs to CloudWatch Logs. [Source: aws/Lambda/Configuring function execution and VPC settings<a name="vpc-config"></a>]

**Step 2: Configure the AWS Lambda Function to Write Logs to CloudWatch Logs**
In the Lambda function configuration, add a new environment variable `AWS_LOGS_GROUP` with the value of your desired log group. This will enable the function to write logs to CloudWatch Logs.

```json
{
  "environment": {
    "variables": {
      "AWS_LOGS_GROUP": "/aws/lambda/<function-name>"
    }
  }
}
```

[Source: aws/Lambda/Configuring function execution and VPC settings<a name="vpc-config"></a>]

**Step 3: Configure the CloudWatch Logs IAM Policy**
Create a new IAM policy that allows your Lambda function to write logs to CloudWatch Logs. The policy should include the following permissions:

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "CloudWatchLogsPolicy",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "logs:CreateLogGroup",
        "logs:CreateLogStream",
        "logs:PutLogEvents"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
```

[Source: aws/ECS/Monitoring your container instances<a name="using_cloudwatch_logs"></a>]

**Step 4: Verify that Logs are Being Written to CloudWatch Logs**
After deploying the Lambda function, verify that logs are being written to CloudWatch Logs by checking the log group in the CloudWatch console.

That's it! By following these steps, you should be able to monitor your AWS Lambda function with CloudWatch.

To secure an Amazon VPC using IAM policies, you can follow these steps:

1. **Allow a specific instance to view resources in other AWS services**:
   - You need to create an IAM policy that restricts access based on the source instance ARN.

   ```json
   {
     "Version": "2012-10-17",
     "Statement": [
       {
         "Effect": "Allow",
         "Action": [
           "ec2:Describe*",
           "elasticloadbalancing:Describe*"
         ],
         "Resource": "*",
         "Condition": {
           "StringEquals": {
             "ec2:SourceInstanceARN": "arn:aws:ec2:us-west-2:123456789012:instance/i-093452212644b0dd6"
           }
         }
       }
     ]
   }
   ```

   **Source:** [AWS > EC2 > Example policies for working with the AWS CLI or an AWS SDK](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access_policies_examples.html#ExamplePolicies_EC2)

2. **Restrict access to a specific Region**:
   - You can use condition keys in your IAM policy to restrict actions based on the Region.

   ```json
   {
     "Version": "2012-10-17",
     "Statement": [
       {
         "Effect": "Allow",
         "Action": [
           "ec2:Describe*"
         ],
         "Resource": "*",
         "Condition": {
           "StringEquals": {
             "aws:RequestedRegion": "us-west-2"
           }
         }
       }
     ]
   }
   ```

   **Source:** [AWS > EC2 > Example policies for working with the AWS CLI or an AWS SDK](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access_policies_examples.html#ExamplePolicies_EC2)

3. **Work with instances, volumes, and snapshots**:
   - You can create more granular policies to control access to specific actions related to EC2 instances, EBS volumes, and EBS snapshots.

   ```json
   {
     "Version": "2012-10-17",
     "Statement": [
       {
         "Effect": "Allow",
         "Action": [
           "ec2:RunInstances",
           "ec2:DescribeVolumes",
           "ec2:CreateSnapshot"
         ],
         "Resource": "*"
       }
     ]
   }
   ```

   **Source:** [AWS > EC2 > Example policies for working with the AWS CLI or an AWS SDK](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access_policies_examples.html#ExamplePolicies_EC2)

4. **Work with IAM roles**:
   - You can create policies that allow specific IAM roles to perform certain actions.

   ```json
   {
     "Version": "2012-10-17",
     "Statement": [
       {
         "Effect": "Allow",
         "Action": [
           "ec2:Describe*"
         ],
         "Resource": "*",
         "Condition": {
           "StringLike": {
             "iam:PassedToPolicyElement": "arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/SpecificRole"
           }
         }
       }
     ]
   }
   ```

   **Source:** [AWS > EC2 > Example policies for working with the AWS CLI or an AWS SDK](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access_policies_examples.html#ExamplePolicies_EC2)

5. **Work with route tables**:
   - You can create policies that allow specific actions on VPC route tables.

   ```json
   {
     "Version": "2012-10-17",
     "Statement": [
       {
         "Effect": "Allow",
         "Action": [
           "ec2:CreateRouteTable",
           "ec2:DeleteRouteTable"
         ],
         "Resource": "*"
       }
     ]
   }
   ```

   **Source:** [AWS > EC2 > Example policies for working with the AWS CLI or an AWS SDK](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access_policies_examples.html#ExamplePolicies_EC2)

By following these steps and using the provided JSON examples, you can create more secure IAM policies to control access within your VPC.

To deploy an application that connects to Azure Blob Storage, you can follow these steps:

1. **Choose Your Language and Deployment Method**
   - For Java SE applications:
     1.1 Use the [Start with a template](storage-quickstart-blobs-java.md?pivots=blob-storage-quickstart-template) option.
       ```java
       // Example of setting up Azure Blob Storage in Java using the Azure SDK for Java
       import com.azure.storage.blob.BlobServiceClient;
       import com.azure.storage.blob.BlobContainerClient;

       public class BlobStorageExample {
           public static void main(String[] args) {
               String connectionString = "your-connection-string";
               BlobServiceClient blobServiceClient = new BlobServiceClientBuilder().connectionString(connectionString).buildClient();
               BlobContainerClient containerClient = blobServiceClient.getBlobContainerClient("container-name");
               // Further code to interact with the storage
           }
       }
       ```
     [Source: azure/Blob Storage/Quickstart: Azure Blob Storage client library for Java SE]

   - For Python applications:
     1.2 Use the [Start with a template](storage-quickstart-blobs-python.md?pivots=blob-storage-quickstart-template) option.
       ```python
       # Example of setting up Azure Blob Storage in Python using the Azure SDK for Python
       from azure.storage.blob import BlobServiceClient

       connection_string = "your-connection-string"
       blob_service_client = BlobServiceClient.from_connection_string(connection_string)
       container_client = blob_service_client.get_container_client("container-name")
       # Further code to interact with the storage
       ```
     [Source: azure/Blob Storage/Quickstart: Azure Blob Storage client library for Python]

   - For .NET applications:
     1.3 Use the [Start with a template](storage-quickstart-blobs-dotnet.md?pivots=blob-storage-quickstart-template) option.
       ```csharp
       // Example of setting up Azure Blob Storage in C# using the Azure SDK for .NET
       using Azure.Storage.Blobs;

       public class BlobStorageExample
       {
           static void Main(string[] args)
           {
               string connectionString = "your-connection-string";
               BlobServiceClient blobServiceClient = new BlobServiceClient(connectionString);
               BlobContainerClient containerClient = blobServiceClient.GetBlobContainerClient("container-name");
               // Further code to interact with the storage
           }
       }
       ```
     [Source: azure/Blob Storage/Quickstart: Azure Blob Storage client library for .NET]

2. **Automate Deployment Tasks Using Azure Developer CLI**
   - Use the Azure Developer CLI to automate deployment tasks and start off with a completed project.
     ```bash
     # Example of using Azure Developer CLI to deploy resources
     azd init --template storage-blob-java
     azd up
     ```
     [Source: azure/Blob Storage/Quickstart: Azure Blob Storage client library for Java SE]

3. **Deploy Your Application**
   - After setting up your project, you can deploy it using the appropriate deployment method.
     ```bash
     # Example of deploying a .NET application to Azure App Service
     az webapp up --name my-app-name --storage-account my-storage-account
     ```
     [Source: azure/Blob Storage/Quickstart: Azure Blob Storage client library for Java SE]

4. **Verify the Deployment**
   - Ensure that your application is correctly connected to and interacting with Azure Blob Storage.
     ```java
     // Example of verifying interaction with Azure Blob Storage in Java
     try {
         containerClient.createIfNotExists();
         System.out.println("Container created or already exists.");
     } catch (Exception e) {
         System.err.println("Error creating container: " + e.getMessage());
     }
     ```
     [Source: azure/Blob Storage/Quickstart: Azure Blob Storage client library for Java SE]

By following these steps, you can deploy an application that connects to Azure Blob Storage using the appropriate SDK and deployment method.

Based on the provided context, it appears that the documentation focuses on deploying a workload on Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) and Google Cloud Functions using Terraform, but not specifically on Google Cloud Pub/Sub. However, I can provide you with steps to create a Pub/Sub function using Terraform as mentioned in the context [Source: gcp/Cloud Functions/Terraform Pub/Sub TutorialStay organized with collections], and then you can use this function to interact with Pub/Sub.

1. First, ensure that you have set up your development environment following the Node.js setup guide ([Source: gcp/GKE/Explore your cluster and workload > Before you begin > Required roles] and [Source: gcp/GCP Cloud Functions/Terraform Pub/Sub TutorialStay organized with collections]).

2. Create a new Terraform configuration file (e.g., `main.tf`) and define the required resources for your Pub/Sub function, such as Cloud Run service, Cloud Build trigger, Cloud Storage bucket, and Artifact Registry repository. Here's an example of a basic configuration:

```hcl
provider "google" {
  project = "<YOUR_PROJECT_ID>"
  region  = "us-central1"
}

locals {
  function_name = "my-pubsub-function"
}

resource "google_cloud_run_service" "default" {
  name       = local.function_name
  location   = var.region
  container_image = "gcr.io/<PROJECT_ID>/${local.function_name}:latest"
}

resource "google_cloudbuild_trigger" "default" {
  name        = "${local.function_name}-trigger"
  description = "Cloud Build trigger for ${local.function_name}"
  service_account = google_service_account.default.email

  build_config = google_cloudbuild_build_config.default.name
}

resource "google_artifact_registry_repository" "default" {
  name = local.function_name
  format = "docker"
}

resource "google_cloudbuild_build_config" "default" {
  name = "${local.function_name}-build"

  build_step {
    name = "gcr.io/cloud-builders/docker"

    args = [
      "build",
      "-t",
      "gcr.io/${google_project().number}/${local.function_name}:latest",
      "."
    ]
  }
}
```

Replace `<YOUR_PROJECT_ID>` with your project ID and update the container image path accordingly.

3. Save this configuration file, then run `terraform init` to initialize Terraform and download required provider plugins.

4. Run `terraform apply` to create all the defined resources in your Google Cloud project.

5. After the resources are created, you can deploy a Pub/Sub function by uploading a function source code zip file to the Cloud Storage bucket that was created for your Cloud Run service. You can use the `gcloud` command-line tool or any other method to upload the zip file.

6. Once the zip file is uploaded, you can create a Pub/Sub topic and subscription, and then bind the Cloud Run service to the subscription. This will allow your function to be triggered whenever a message is published to the topic. For more information on how to do this, refer to the [Google Cloud Pub/Sub documentation](https://cloud.google.com/pubsub/docs/overview).

7. Finally, you can test your Pub/Sub function by publishing a message to the topic and verifying that the function is triggered and processes the message as expected.
